His most expensive sculpture cost almost $71,000 (£44,000) and was constructed over five days using 200 tons of sand. 

Mr Long said there is a process to follow goes each sculpture that starts with a base pile of wet sand.

He said: 'You carve from the top down as you go, if you don't follow these steps you will be starting over.

'The quality of the sand is very important - it should to be fine and have an angular grain structure.'

To preserve sculptures, he mixes water-based glue with water and sprays it on top of the sculpture.

The sand sculptures can stand for up to four months when coated with the mixture - and even withstood a hurricane.

